</div>
{{Blurimage|file=96e5fc03ffd7731b3b62eae19cfe2bbf.jpg|caption=As The 90s Past|align=left}}
Back to '93, also known as "Level 93", is a large suburban house which resembling an American house built around the 1990s. The level has multiple rooms which consist of living rooms, bedrooms, kitchens, etc. While the layout resembles that of a normal family home, many areas feel strangely artificial. The level is very quiet, with only the occasional sound of floorboards creaking or televisions. Family photographs and other everyday household items can be found throughout the house.

Most rooms are fully furnished with furniture which also dates from around the 80s to late 90s. Landline phones can be found inside the kitchens and the living room. If one picks the phone and calls a number then they will be meet with a dead line with nothing but static on the other side. Ovens and microwaves work alongside the fridge inside the kitchen. The house is generally in good condition, although some rooms might have faded wallpaper.

The layout is mostly open, though some areas are more complex than others. The level is much larger than a normal suburban house, but it is not infinite. A large basement is located beneath the house, while an attic extends across most of the upper floor.

Electricity is present throughout the entire level. Ceiling lights, lamps, and televisions are powered by an unknown source. Windows emit a soft yellow light and cannot be seen through. Breaking a window reveals only more yellow space beyond the glass.

The windows emit a soft yellow glow and cannot be seen through. Breaking a window reveals a thick yellow fog beyond the glass. The fog quickly fades into a seemingly endless void, with no visible end.

Wanderers may discover bedrooms that resemble those they had during their childhood. This phenomenon occurs regardless of an individual's age or where one is from. Those born after the 90s have also reported discovering bedrooms from their own childhood, despite the level which takes place in the 1990s. The layout, furniture, and wall colors usually match their memories from that time.

These bedrooms are somewhat common and appear without any clear pattern. Not every person encounters one, and those who do are rarely able to find the room again after leaving it. Reports also suggest that different people will see different bedrooms, even when exploring the same area. The phenomenon is believed to be different for each person who enters; its exact cause remains unknown.
